07/06/2005
WASHINGTON, United States -- President George W. Bush is to meet with Turkish Prime Minister Recep Tayyip Erdogan on Wednesday (8 June) at the White House.
Aides say the two leaders will discuss joint action "to advance freedom in Iraq and the broader Middle East, Central Asia and the Caucasus".
Bush is also expected to voice support for Ankara's bid to join the EU.
Also on the agenda are prospects for the reunification of Cyprus.
Erdogan plans to discuss the matter with UN Secretary General Kofi Annan in New York.
In other news, an earthquake measuring 5.7 on the Richter scale has rocked the Turkish province of Bingol, injuring more than 40 people.
The government closed schools in the area and asked authorities and relief organisations to provide tents.
(AFP, NTV, AFP - 07/06/05;
Turks.US, Voice of America, TurkishPress.com - 06/06/05)
